There are two different `&amp;` operators.

The bitwise AND operator (&amp;) compares each bit of the first operand to the corresponding bit of the second operand. If both bits are 1, the corresponding result bit is set to 1. Otherwise, the corresponding result bit is set to 0.

Both operands to the bitwise AND operator must be of integral types.

For example:

    #include &lt;iostream&gt;

    using namespace std;

    int main() {
       unsigned short a = 0xFFFF;      // pattern 1111 ...
       unsigned short b = 0xAAAA;      // pattern 1010 ...
    
       cout  &lt;&lt; hex &lt;&lt; ( a &amp; b ) &lt;&lt; endl;   // prints &quot;aaaa&quot;, pattern 1010 ...
    }

Since `ip` is a `dict`, you must use `.items` to access both keys and values:

    {% for index, data in ip.items %}
      &lt;p&gt;Your data #{{ index }} is &lt;strong&gt;{{ data }}&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
    {% endfor %}

Since `data` is a single item `list` itself, you must get the first (`0`th) element and use the following syntax to access items:

    {{ data.0.DOUBLIN }}

